The IAS in $^{52}$Co decays 75(23)\% of the time by $\gamma$ rays and in 25(5)\% by (isospin-forbidden) proton emission to the ground state in $^{51}$Fe ($J^{\pi}$ = 5/2$^{-}$). The population of the first excited state at 253 keV ($J^{\pi}$ = 7/2$^{-}$) in $^{51}$Fe via proton decay would require the observation of a $\gamma$ ray at 253 keV that we do not see. The $\gamma$ branch from the IAS proceeds via the $\gamma$ rays of 2407 and 141 keV which populate the levels in $^{52}$Co at 518 and 378 keV, respectively, while no $\gamma$ rays are observed from the level at 378 keV. As explained in detail in Section \ref{masses}, the energy of the 2$^+$ level at 378 keV is assumed from the value in the mirror nucleus $^{52}$Mn, 377.749(5) keV \cite{NDS2015}, and fixes the excitation energy scale for the $^{52}$Co levels. Barrier-penetration calculations give a partial proton half-life of $t_{1/2}\sim10^{-15}$ s for the decay of the IAS to the ground state in $^{51}$Fe, and the calculated Weisskopf transition probability for the $\gamma$ decay of the IAS to the 1$^{+}$ level at 518 keV is of the same order-of-magnitude. In the mirror nucleus $^{52}$Mn the 2$^+$ level at 378 keV is an isomer with a half-life of 21.1 min. Hence the 2$^+$ level in $^{52}$Co is also likely to be an isomeric state decaying by $\beta$ emission to $^{52}$Fe.

